This is a textbook case of **coverage-gaming** — every production method is called, achieving high line coverage, but almost nothing is actually verified. Here's the severity-ranked audit:

---

## 🔴 Critical — Assert-Free Tests (fire-and-forget)

These tests call production code but have **zero assertions**. They'll pass even if the code does the wrong thing entirely.

**1. `AddProduct_Works` (line 17)** — No assertion that the product was stored.
```csharp
// FIX: verify round-trip
_catalog.AddProduct(product);
var result = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(result);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", result.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, result.Price);
```

**2. `UpdatePrice_Works` (line 32)** — Calls `UpdatePrice` but never checks the new price persisted.
```csharp
// FIX: assert the price actually changed
_catalog.UpdatePrice("SKU-001", 14.99m);
var updated = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.AreEqual(14.99m, updated!.Price);
```

**3. `RemoveProduct_Works` (line 38)** — Calls `RemoveProduct` but never checks the product is gone.
```csharp
// FIX: assert product no longer exists
_catalog.RemoveProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNull(_catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001"));
```

**4. `GetProductCount_Works` (line 63)** — No assertion at all, and tests on an **empty** catalog so even coverage is trivial.
```csharp
// FIX: assert correct count
_catalog.AddProduct(new Product("SKU-001", "Widget", 9.99m));
var count = _catalog.GetProductCount();
Assert.AreEqual(1, count);
```

**5. `ApplyBulkDiscount_Works` (line 68)** — Applies 10% discount but never checks any price changed.
```csharp
// FIX: assert discounted prices
_catalog.ApplyBulkDiscount(0.10m);
Assert.AreEqual(8.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001")!.Price);
Assert.AreEqual(17.991m, _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-002")!.Price);
```

**6. `ImportFromCsv_Works` (line 84)** — Imports a row but never verifies the product exists afterward.
```csharp
// FIX: verify imported product
_catalog.ImportFromCsv("SKU-001,Widget,9.99");
var p = _catalog.GetProduct("SKU-001");
Assert.IsNotNull(p);
Assert.AreEqual("Widget", p.Name);
Assert.AreEqual(9.99m, p.Price);
```

---

## 🟠 High — Weak Assertions (assert-not-null-only)

These tests assert `IsNotNull` but never check **values**, so they'd pass even if every field were wrong.

